  "summary": "The LSP subprocesses spawned by the manager become zombie processes when they idle or time out because the LSPClient.stop() method, which would terminate the subprocess, is never invoked. The missing reaping logic in agent/lsp/manager.py must track idle connections and call stop() on the corresponding LSPClient when a timeout occurs.",
  "references": ["https://docs.python.org/3/library/subprocess.html#subprocess.Popen.wait", "https://docs.python.org/3/library/subprocess.html#subprocess.Popen.kill"],
  "keywords": ["LSP", "subprocess", "reaping", "idle", "timeout", "zombie", "resource leak", "process management"],
  "analysis": "The issue is a classic child-process reaping problem. The LSP manager creates subprocesses for language servers but does not handle their termination when they become idle. The LSPClient class already has a stop() method (likely calling Popen.kill() or terminate()), but it is not called from the manager's timeout logic. The fix requires modifying the manager to monitor idle time and invoke client.stop() when the threshold is reached, preventing resource leaks. The primary authoritative reference is the Python subprocess module documentation, which details the need to explicitly wait for or kill child processes to avoid zombies."
